Atlas Kitchen is back after a 7mo Covid hiatus. So why are you--my UWS friends--still dining at dumpy standbys in the W. 80s & 70s? Atlas is real Chinese food by a truly inventive chef. Pictured here is the other-worldly cumin lamb, mustard greens w- bok choy, and a pork soup for the picky eater at the table. Yes, many of us will need to challenge ourselves and order the pig trotter & fish head entrees recommended by Eater & others; it was just my 1st visit, so will need the company of other adventurous diners to make those entrees worth it. Attentive, friendly service. Pretty, calm-inducing decor. And all Covid dining rules were being followed.

I don’t want to say this but I think restaurant at these price should not use frozen pork soup dumplings from the Chinese market.  It’s pretty good tho , but they are directly from the market with the packaging. So does the scallion pancake. You can tell by the food recipes is slightly changed so they changed the chef definitely.  If you are careful, you can notice that they have a five-star rating and are guides... They spend a lot of money to promote the restaurant.  Marketing methods can't hide that some customers have diarrhea.

There are many choices here, my friends recommended Chicken Feet w/ Two Spices, and I also ordered Thin Slices of Poached Beef w/ Chef Special Spicy Sauce and Spicy Duck Tongue and Baby Cabbage in Ham Broth! Fresh, quite rich feeling!
Great Saute ́ed Pork Intestine w/ Green Pepper, I think it’s only available here, big and fast! Will come next time.

Instead of trying to replicate the business models of SG/HHH and the likes, Atlas is a valuable addition to UWS community for providing a premium option of classic Szechuan cuisine. The vibe makes it an excellent place to introduce authentic Szechuan food to friends, and the food has so far been consistently good. Waitstaffs are helpful. Their unique "green" spicy boiled fish is a great place to start, although you might have to specifically ask for it and it sometimes disappear from the menu. Stay away from things like potato with vegetable.

To give a fair evaluation, it is worth encouraging to insist on business during the epidemic, but hope the restaurant can pay attention to hygiene! ! ! First of all, there is no protection from the outside world in the store. Second, their cashier actually packs it? ? ? Moreover, their chef actually sits close to the door without any protective measures! Many delivery staff who take out takeout haven't done any protective measures at all! ! ! ! This makes me feel very scared. Although the food is delicious, it makes me feel psychologically stressed. I hope the restaurant can do food protection measures, I do not want to be infected with covid19.

The best chic restaurant near the university!!! Variety of choices of dishes - chicken, pork, beef, sea food - you name it! Definitely in love with the vibe, decorations, and the food.  The wall painting is from artist Qiu An Xiong whose work was collected by MoMA. A rare see immersive artsy dining experience!  You need to be here as many times as you can to explore the full menu.  Absolutely a must go!

Beautiful, clean, affordable and great service. I can tell the owner and the management team poured lots of heart into it. The food is great too. Can't believe that some of the reviews here are so negative. My favorite dish there is the dry wok cauliflower and I'll highly recommend it no matter you like authentic Chinese food or not.

Inconsistent experience. The first time we came a few weeks ago, our meal was fine. The second time, we were extremely disappointed with our dinner. The waiter carried the soup we ordered with his finger on the inside of the bowl. They immediately brought the main dish after. We ordered the General Tso, and the rice was cold by the time we finished the soup (which we probably shouldn't have had after the finger) and the chicken was hard and tough. The employee at the cash register listened to our issues with the service as we were leaving, but nothing was done.

The food was ok - authentic but pricey for its portion and average quality. The environment was nice. But beef shank came looking not fresh, and the morning after two family members who had had that got sick. I’m thinking about suing them being miserable lying in bed on a Saturday.

This place is great. It has the best Chinese food in the Upper West Side. Their pork soup dumplings are marvelous, as well as their scallion pancakes and steak. The soup dumplings have very nice soup inside them, though they are a bit too soft. The scallion pancakes are soft and delicious. The steak is soft, spicy, and they taste like steak should taste like. They have Green Tea and Black Tea. The service was good. The people that work at Atlas Kitchen do their job well. They are fast and efficient. But they are not talkative at all. I loved the seats here. They have very comfortable booths and chairs. The tables were also very nice. The floor had a lovely pattern on it. That was nice. The atmosphere is good. When I went, the place was quiet, had nice music and was overall very nice. But it was not extremely quiet. That would have been bad.
